definitions.definition: To cover, fill, or affect with lead
definitions.example: continuous firing leads the grooves of a rifle.

definitions.definition: To place leads between the lines of.

To guide or conduct, as by accompanying, going before, showing, influencing, directing with authority, etc.; to have precedence or preeminence; to be first or chief; — used in most of the senses of the transitive verb.
To draw or direct by influence, whether good or bad; to prevail on; to induce; to entice; to allure
definitions.example: to lead someone to a righteous cause

definitions.definition: To tend or reach in a certain direction, or to a certain place.
definitions.example: the path leads to the mill;  gambling leads to other vices
The shock led to a change in his behaviour.

definitions.definition: (transitive) To live or experience (a particular way of life).

definitions.example: Avoid leading questions if you really want the truth.
He is a leading supplier of plumbing supplies in the county.
The stock market can be a leading economic indicator.

definitions.definition: An act by which one is led or guided.
Vertical space added between lines; line spacing.
